    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>General Methods</title>
            <para>Water from a discrete sample is filtered using 0.45 HA filters. Filters are frozen at -70 degrees Celsius for a minimum of 24 hours and a maximum of 12 months. The filters are then extracted in 90% acetone and stored at -20 degrees Celsius for an additional 24 hours. A digital Turner fluorometer is used to read fluorescence. Chlorophyll is calculated from fluorescence (Smith et al,1981). Chlorophyll analysis performed in the Spring at Palmer Station by LTER Palmer participants. Sampling is as follows: 1. Collect a sample of seawater from the SW Intake in the pump house; 2. Let the seawater run out of the hose at a moderate rate for 2-3 minutes to clear the hose of contaminating water; 3. Rinse a 250 mL sampling bottle 3 times and fill; 4. Return to lab and filter approximately 200 mL onto a 0.45 HA filter, working in subdued light (no overheard lights on); 5. Rinse filter unit and grad cylinder with filtered seawater; 6. Place filter in a numbered scintillation vial and put vial in a tray in -70C freezer; 7. Retain for LTER participants to analyze.; 8. Log results on Excel spreadsheet and save in LTER folder on PAL network.</para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Frequency</title>
            <para>approximately weekly some years</para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
    </methods>
